<div id="review_2929144376" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2929144376" />
    <a title="Indran Fernando" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30920756-indran-fernando"><img alt="Indran Fernando" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1463204281p2/30920756.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2929144376?book_show_action=true">Aug 13, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Indran Fernando" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Indran Fernando" href="/user/show/30920756-indran-fernando">Indran Fernando</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2929144376" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2998440865660260886">Can&apos;t quite give this a 3. Found it to have fewer ideas than I expected. Some things in this book are debatable but they are presented with what I took as an almost smug matter-of-factness. In general, it&apos;s a book that could resonate more or less depending on one&apos;s mood, and right now my mood is more of a no-BS one. For example I noticed Hanh likes to use the mystical-sounding construction &quot;A is B. And so to we may recognize that B... is A!&quot; Or something like, &apos;we need to not just sit in silence</span>
  <span id="freeText2998440865660260886" style="display:none">Can't quite give this a 3. Found it to have fewer ideas than I expected. Some things in this book are debatable but they are presented with what I took as an almost smug matter-of-factness. In general, it's a book that could resonate more or less depending on one's mood, and right now my mood is more of a no-BS one. For example I noticed Hanh likes to use the mystical-sounding construction "A is B. And so to we may recognize that B... is A!" Or something like, 'we need to not just sit in silence, but for silence....to sit in us!' Which makes me roll my eyes a bit.<br /><br />Secondly, I get the utility of practicing radical empathy towards violent criminals, and having compassion towards all animals. Plants too? Hmm, I would want to add some caveats since they don't feel pain. Minerals too? Hanh could have spent a little less time on mineral empathy and more demonstrating humility by acknowledging the abundance of violent and hypocritical manifestations of Buddhism in the world today (which, to be fair, he has done elsewhere).<br /><br />When he muses (I paraphrase) that protestors would do well to instead go and sit in silence somewhere, or make their demands in a more loving way, because after all political leaders are people to and want to be talked to respectfully just like any of the rest of us-- I can't help but cringe.<br /><br />It seems second nature for him to criticize American society, and praise Buddhists' principles of nonviolence, but where was that place where I saw stray dogs getting rocks thrown at them? Was that the US?.. Was it Peru, or Egypt..? Nope, that was Sri Lanka, and the rocks were being thrown by the most pious and self-righteous of Buddhist monks. Is it Hanh's job to answer for that? No; but I felt this book was a bit naive at times, offering a strangely simplified and self-assured worldview. <br /><br />I am glad I read this book, but given its abstract, emotive, ahistorical bent, it felt useful to remind myself afterwards how Buddhism, too, manifests in violent nationalist movements--- <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddhism_and_violence?wprov=sfla1">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddhis...</a> (You'll note that Hanh, to his credit, is listed among Buddhist figures who has spoken out against violence against Muslims in Myanmar.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="2998440865660260886" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


